    "rationale": "The FEA modeling framework for non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw ASTM F1717 compression-bending is accepted for the stated COU at MRL 3 (Medium assurance). Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels. All three primary QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) satisfy both acceptance criteria (relative error < 10%; E/uval < 1.96) across all N=11 specimens and both independent laboratories. The sensitivity analysis confirms that QoI predictions are robust to material property and contact stiffness uncertainty. The single shortfall — Test conditions achieving Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 3 — is addressed by the offset rationale below and does not undermine the overall credibility conclusion given the regulatory standardization of the ASTM F1717 test condition and the documented rate insensitivity of Ti-6Al-4V at the relevant strain rates. The multi-laboratory validation design, specimen-specific geometry modeling, and complete input equivalency traceability collectively provide confidence sufficient for a Medium assurance regulatory submission.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z",
    "hasOffsetRationale": [
      {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/offset/test-conditions-shortfall",
        "type": "OffsetRationale",
        "name": "Offset rationale for Test conditions shortfall (Gradation 2 vs. required 3)",
        "description": "The Test conditions factor achieved Gradation 2 (single ASTM F1717 standard condition) against a required Gradation 3 (two or more conditions bracketing the use space). This shortfall is justified on three grounds: (1) ASTM F1717 specifies a single quasi-static compression-bending condition as the regulatory standard for pedicle screw construct evaluation, and FDA guidance accepts this condition as sufficient for 510(k) submissions; (2) the strain rate sensitivity of Ti-6Al-4V ELI is negligible below 0.01 s⁻¹ (well-established in the open literature, including Lesuer et al. 2001), and the test strain rate of < 0.001 s⁻¹ is two orders of magnitude below the threshold for rate-dependent effects; (3) the remaining twelve factors all meet or exceed their required levels, and the combined validation uncertainty (E/uval ≤ 1.31 across all QoIs) provides substantial margin against the 1.96 acceptance threshold. The offset is therefore considered adequate to support an Accepted outcome at Medium assurance.",
